```java
public class InsertionSort {

    /**
     * Sorts an array of integers using the Insertion Sort algorithm.
     * Insertion sort iterates, consuming one input element each repetition,
     * and building a sorted output list. Each iteration removes one element
     * from the input data, finds the location it belongs within the sorted list,
     * and inserts it there. It repeats until no input elements remain.
     *
     * @param arr The array of integers to be sorted.
     */
    public static void sort(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        for (int i = 1; i < n; i++) {
            int key = arr[i]; // Element to be inserted into the sorted sub-array
            int j = i - 1;

            // Move elements of arr[0..i-1], that are greater than key,
            // to one position ahead of their current position
            while (j >= 0 && arr[j] > key) {
                arr[j + 1] = arr[j];
                j = j - 1;
            }
            arr[j + 1] = key; // Place the key in its correct position
        }
    }

    /**
     * A utility method to print the array.
     * @param arr The array to be printed.
     */
    public static void printArray(int[] arr) {
        for (int i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
            System.out.print(arr[i] + " ");
        }
        System.out.println();
    }

    // Main method to test the Insertion Sort algorithm
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr = {12, 11, 13, 5, 6};
        System.out.println("Original array:");
        printArray(arr);

        sort(arr);

        System.out.println("Sorted array:");
        printArray(arr);

        int[] arr2 = {5, 1, 4, 2, 8};
        System.out.println("\nOriginal array 2:");
        printArray(arr2);

        sort(arr2);

        System.out.println("Sorted array 2:");
        printArray(arr2);
    }
}
```

**Explanation:**

1.  **`sort(int[] arr)` method:**
    *   The outer `for` loop iterates from the second element (`i = 1`) to the end of the array. The first element (`arr[0]`) is considered to be a sorted sub-array of size 1.
    *   `int key = arr[i];` stores the current element that needs to be inserted into its correct position within the already sorted part of the array (`arr[0...i-1]`).
    *   `int j = i - 1;` initializes `j` to the last index of the sorted sub-array.
    *   The `while` loop compares `key` with elements in the sorted sub-array (`arr[j]`).
        *   If an element `arr[j]` is greater than `key`, it means `key` should be inserted before `arr[j]`. So, `arr[j]` is shifted one position to the right (`arr[j + 1] = arr[j];`).
        *   `j` is decremented to move to the previous element in the sorted sub-array.
    *   This shifting continues until `j` becomes less than 0 (meaning `key` is the smallest element and should be placed at the beginning) or an element `arr[j]` is found that is less than or equal to `key`.
    *   `arr[j + 1] = key;` finally places `key` into its correct sorted position.

